streams_utm2La Selva GIS Coverageshttp://www.ots.duke.edu/
The ARC/INFO coverage, STREAMS, describes streams at La Selva Biological Station, Costa Rica. The STREAMS coverage is part of the GIS laboratory database developed to support research, education and administrative management for LSBS. EnglishStreams were derived by modeling how water flows through a digital elevation model (DEM) of La Selva. The DEM used was derived from LIDAR imagery (otsdb/dem/dem_msl) and had a 10-m resolution. Original research was completed by José Antonio Guzmán Alvarez (see cross-reference citation). Streams in flat, alluvial areas were updated with grid survey information and GPS points with work by Matthew Clark (GIS Laboratory Manager) and Sara Chamberlain (GIS laboratory volunteer). Information on the source of each stream segment is contained within the coverage.

See Guzman 1999 cross-reference for a thorough description of the spatial accuracy of the streams in this coverage. There is an Adobe Acrobat PDF file available from the La Selva GIS laboratory manager. GPS points were differentially corrected and are thought to have a horizontal accuracy of 3 to 8 m. Survey points have the same accuracy as the grid tubes, which is thought to be decimeter accuracy. 60 tubes were measured by Guzman (1999) that were within 10m of the modeled streams (before adjustments made with GPS and survey points). The actual distance from the tube to the stream was then measured in the field. A tally of actual distance to the tube for all streams, regardless of order, is summarized below. More information on methodology and a detailed discussion of stream order accuracy can be found in the document cited in the cross references.

The LIDAR-derived DEM was filled for sinks, a flow accumulation GRID was computed and then streams were delineated by selecting all GRID areas were flow accumulation was greater than 100. The resulting binary GRID was ordered using the STREAMORDER command. This raster stream order map was then tranformed into a vector line coverage using the STREAMLINE command. Arc/Info v8.0.203/15/01 Original STREAMLINE coverage was edited extensively to remove obvious erroneous lines. Stream lines, especially in flat areas, were modified to snap to a database of known stream location points. These points either came from DGPS readings in the field (i.e, from the stream edge or floating/walking in the center of the stream) or from points were the LS grid tube survey crossed the stream and measured the X, Y location (found in QCOV). Additional streams and rivers outside of the La Selva reserve were digitzed from an August 2000 IKONOS satellite image, whereas finer detail was retained from the DEM-generated streams. This streams coverage was made primarily from grid-tube survey points at stream/tube transect intersections. Streams were derived by modeling how water flows through a digital elevation model (DEM) of La Selva. The DEM used was derived from LIDAR imagery (otsdb/dem/dem_msl) and had a 10-m resolution. Original research was completed by José Antonio Guzmán Alvarez (see cross-reference citation). Streams were updated with grid survey stream-crossing point information and GPS points with work by Matthew Clark (GIS Laboratory Manager) and Sara Chamberlain (GIS laboratory volunteer). Most problem area were found to be in flat, alluvial terraces, were the GIS water flow model was less accurate. Other problem areas not corrected are shown in the enclosure map. Information on the source of each stream segment is contained within the coverage.Lines represent streams. First order streams are really depressions with ephemeral flow (i.e., during rain events). Stream orders 6 and 7 are rivers.
